.TH "TEMPORAL.DURATION.DAYS" "3JS" "December 8, 2025" "JavaScript" "JavaScript Reference Manual"
.SH NAME
Temporal.Duration.days \- Temporal.Duration.prototype.days
.SH SYNOPSIS
The \f[B]\f[CB]days\f[B]\f[R] accessor property of
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] instances returns an integer representing
the number of days in the duration.
.PP
Unless the duration is balanced, you cannot assume the range of this
value, but you can know its sign by checking the duration\(cqs
\f[CR]sign\f[R] property.
If it is balanced to a unit above days, the \f[CR]days\f[R] absolute
value\(cqs range depends on the calendar (how many days are in a week or
month).
.PP
The set accessor of \f[CR]days\f[R] is \f[CR]undefined\f[R].
You cannot change this property directly.
Use the \f[CR]with()\f[R] method to create a new
\f[CR]Temporal.Duration\f[R] object with the desired new value.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS Using days
.IP
.EX
\f[B]const\f[R] d1 = Temporal.Duration.from({ weeks: 1, days: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d2 = Temporal.Duration.from({ weeks: \-1, days: \-1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d3 = Temporal.Duration.from({ weeks: 1 });
\f[B]const\f[R] d4 = Temporal.Duration.from({ days: 7 });

console.log(d1.days); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
console.log(d2.days); \f[I]// \-1\f[R]
console.log(d3.days); \f[I]// 0\f[R]
console.log(d4.days); \f[I]// 7\f[R]

\f[I]// Balance d4\f[R]
\f[B]const\f[R] d4Balanced = d4.round({
  largestUnit: \(dqweeks\(dq,
  relativeTo: Temporal.PlainDate.from(\(dq2021\-01\-01\(dq), \f[I]// ISO 8601 calendar\f[R]
});
console.log(d4Balanced.days); \f[I]// 0\f[R]
console.log(d4Balanced.weeks); \f[I]// 1\f[R]
.EE
